## Diagnosis — Where the Time Actually Goes

Real-world logs on Z: drive (USB/external) reveal the **grouping phase is the #1 bottleneck**, not hashing:

| Phase | Scan 1 (2 812 files) | Scan 2 (5 777 files) | % of total (Scan 2) |
|-------|---------------------|---------------------|---------------------|
| Directory walk | 0.63 s | 4.54 s | 0.7% |
| File stat | 1.41 s | 1.93 s | 0.3% |
| Hashing (3a+3b) | 65.98 s | 156.34 s | 23% |
| **Grouping** | **108.11 s** | **515.68 s** | **76%** |
| **Total** | **178.93 s** | **676.55 s** | |

### Root cause: `ExtractMetadata` opens each file 3 times on a slow drive

`ExtractMetadata` (called for every image in every duplicate group) performs:
1. `os.Stat(path)` — 1 file open
2. `os.Open(path)` + `image.DecodeConfig` — 2nd file open (for dimensions)
3. `os.Open(path)` + `exif.Decode` — 3rd file open (for EXIF data)

On SSD this takes ~8 ms/file. On USB/NAS (Z: drive), each open costs ~50 ms,
so it's ~173 ms/file. For 2 972 metadata files in Scan 2: **2 972 × 173 ms ≈ 514 s**.

### Second root cause: Too many files in perceptual groups

Scan 2 has 2 972 files across only 121 groups = **24.6 files/group average**.
Many of these are burst/series shots (same scene, same second, sequential filenames)
that the current series detector misses because it requires **strictly consecutive**
filenames (gap ≤ 1). iPhone naming sometimes skips numbers
(IMG_4446, IMG_4448, IMG_4450) which breaks the gap=1 rule.

