### Optimization B — Early Series Detection (skip metadata for series when excluded)

**Impact: If 50% of perceptual groups are series and IncludeSeries=false, saves ~257s on Scan 2**

Currently, `detectSeriesGroups` runs AFTER all metadata has been extracted. If the user
doesn't want series, we're doing expensive metadata extraction for nothing.

#### New approach: detect series BEFORE expensive metadata extraction

After the BK-Tree pass (Pass 2) but BEFORE `parallelExtractMetadata`:

1. For each perceptual group with confidence ≥ 95%, do a **lightweight series check**
   using only filename pattern matching (Criterion A — no file I/O needed).
2. If `IncludeSeries=false`, remove detected series groups from the metadata list entirely.
3. The remaining groups still go through full metadata extraction.
4. After metadata extraction, run the full `isSeriesGroup` (including Criterion B,
   time+camera) on remaining high-confidence groups.

```go
// In GroupDuplicates, after findPerceptualPaths, BEFORE parallelExtractMetadata:

if !includeSeries {
    // Lightweight pre-filter: remove filename-sequential groups before metadata extraction.
    // This avoids opening thousands of series files on slow drives.
    for root, paths := range percGroups {
        if len(paths) < 2 {
            continue
        }
        // Quick filename-only check (no file I/O).
        if percMinDist[root] <= 3 { // High confidence = likely series
            if isFilenameSeriesFromPaths(paths) {
                delete(percGroups, root) // Remove from perceptual groups entirely.
            }
        }
    }
    fmt.Printf("[grouper] Pre-filtered series groups. Remaining perceptual: %d\n", len(percGroups))
}
```

Create `isFilenameSeriesFromPaths` that works directly on paths (no ImageMetadata needed):

```go
// isFilenameSeriesFromPaths checks if a list of file paths have sequential
// filenames (relaxed gap ≤ 5). This is a lightweight check that requires no
// file I/O — it only looks at the path strings.
func isFilenameSeriesFromPaths(paths []string) bool {
    if len(paths) < 2 {
        return false
    }
    type parsed struct {
        prefix string
        number int
    }
    var items []parsed
    for _, p := range paths {
        base := filepath.Base(p)
        stem := strings.TrimSuffix(base, filepath.Ext(base))
        m := numericSuffixRegex.FindStringSubmatch(stem)
        if m == nil {
            return false
        }
        num, err := strconv.Atoi(m[2])
        if err != nil {
            return false
        }
        items = append(items, parsed{prefix: strings.ToLower(m[1]), number: num})
    }
    // All same prefix.
    for i := 1; i < len(items); i++ {
        if items[i].prefix != items[0].prefix {
            return false
        }
    }
    // Sorted suffixes: max gap ≤ 5.
    sort.Slice(items, func(i, j int) bool { return items[i].number < items[j].number })
    for i := 1; i < len(items); i++ {
        if gap := items[i].number - items[i-1].number; gap < 0 || gap > 5 {
            return false
        }
    }
    return true
}
```

### Optimization C — Reduce Perceptual Hash I/O (Phase 3b buffer reuse)

**Impact: Moderate (saves ~10-15s on Scan 2)**

In `computeDHashFromHeader`, each call allocates a fresh 128 KB buffer:
```go
buf := make([]byte, 128*1024) // line 430
```

Replace with a `sync.Pool` of 128 KB buffers (similar to the existing `bufPool` for 64 KB):

```go
// headerBufPool holds reusable 128 KB buffers for computeDHashFromHeader.
var headerBufPool = sync.Pool{
    New: func() interface{} {
        buf := make([]byte, 128*1024)
        return &buf
    },
}
```

In `computeDHashFromHeader`:
```go
bufPtr := headerBufPool.Get().(*[]byte)
buf := *bufPtr
n, _ := io.ReadFull(f, buf)
f.Close()
// ... use buf[:n] ...
// At the end (all return paths), put buffer back:
headerBufPool.Put(bufPtr)
```

This eliminates ~6000 allocations of 128 KB each, reducing GC pressure significantly.

